import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for industry in data['series'].unique():
        industry_data = data[data['series'] == industry]
        plt.plot(industry_data['date'], industry_data['rate'], label=industry)
    
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    avg_unemployment_rate = data.groupby('series')['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    avg_unemployment_rate = avg_unemployment_rate.sort_values('rate', ascending=False)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.bar(avg_unemployment_rate['series'], avg_unemployment_rate['rate'], color='tab:blue')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Average Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('Which industry has the highest average unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    
    max_rate = avg_unemployment_rate['rate'].max()
    max_industry = avg_unemployment_rate.loc[avg_unemployment_rate['rate'] == max_rate, 'series'].values[0]
    plt.axhline(max_rate, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Highest Rate: {max_industry} ({max_rate:.2f})')
    plt.legend()
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.hist(data['rate'], bins=20, color='blue', alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['rate'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['rate'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment rate across all industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data['month'] = data['date'].dt.month

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    data.boxplot(column='rate', by='month', ax=ax)
    ax.set_title('How does the unemployment rate vary across different months of the year?')
    ax.set_xlabel('Month')
    ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.suptitle('')  # Remove automatic title
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Unemployment Rate', loc='upper right')

    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['rate'], data['count'], c=data['series'].astype('category').cat.codes, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.5)
    ax.set_xlabel('Unemployment Rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of Unemployed People')
    ax.set_title('What is the relationship between unemployment rate and the number of unemployed people?', wrap=True)

    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Industries")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
